#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:112
msgid "#### Multitask"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:114
msgid ""
"Linux belongs to the family of time-sharing operating systems. It shares "
"process time between several programs, switching from one to another in a "
"transparent way for the user. This implies:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:119
msgid "simultaneous execution of several programs;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:119
msgid "distribution of CPU time by the scheduler;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:119
msgid "reduction of problems due to a failed application;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:119
msgid "reduced performance when there are too many programs running."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:121
msgid "#### Multi user"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:123
msgid ""
"The purpose of Multics was to allow several users to work from several "
"terminals (screen and keyboard) on a single computer (very expensive at the "
"time). Linux, which is inspired by this operating system, has kept this "
"ability to work with several users simultaneously and independently, each "
"one having its own user account, memory space and access rights to files and "
"software."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:125
msgid "#### Multiprocessor"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:127
msgid ""
"Linux is able to work with multi-processor computers or with multi-core "
"processors."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:129
msgid "#### Multi platform"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:131
msgid ""
"Linux is written in a high-level language that can be adapted to different "
"types of platforms during compilation. It therefore runs on :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:138
msgid "home computers (PC or laptop);"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:138
msgid "servers (data, applications,...);"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:138
msgid "portable computers (smartphones or tablets)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:138
msgid "embedded systems (car computer);"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:138
msgid "active network elements (routers, switches)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:138
msgid "household appliances (TVs, refrigerators,...)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:140
msgid "#### Open"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:142
msgid ""
"Linux is based on recognized standards [posix](http://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/"
"POSIX), TCP/IP, NFS, Samba ... allowing to share data and services with "
"other application systems."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:144
msgid "### The UNIX/Linux philosophy"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:151
msgid "Everything is a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:151
msgid "Portability."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:151
msgid "Do only one thing and do it well."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:151
msgid "KISS: Keep It Simple Stupid."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:151
msgid ""
"\"UNIX is basically a simple operating system, but you have to be a genius "
"to understand the simplicity.\" (__Dennis Ritchie__)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:151
msgid ""
"\"Unix is user-friendly. It just isn't promiscuous about which users it's "
"friendly with.\" (__Steven King__)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:153
msgid "## The GNU/LINUX distributions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:155
msgid ""
"A Linux distribution is a **consistent set of software** assembled around "
"the Linux kernel and ready to be installed along with the necessary "
"components to manage this software (installation, removal, configuration). "
"There are **associative or community** distributions (Debian, Rocky) or "
"**commercial** (RedHat, Ubuntu)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:157
msgid ""
"Each distribution offers one or more **desktop environments**, provides a "
"set of pre-installed software and a library of additional software. "
"Configuration options (kernel or services options for example) are specific "
"to each one."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:159
msgid ""
"This principle allows you to have distributions oriented to **beginners** "
"(Ubuntu, Linux Mint...), to have a more complex approach (Gentoo, Arch), to "
"be focused more towards **servers** (Debian, Redhat), or to be dedicated "
"towards **workstations**."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:161
msgid "### Desktop environments"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:163
msgid ""
"There are many graphic environments: **Gnome**, **KDE**, **LXDE**, **XFCE**, "
"etc. There is something for everyone, and their **ergonomics** have nothing "
"to be ashamed of when compared to Microsoft or Apple systems!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:165
msgid ""
"So why is there so little enthusiasm for Linux, when **there are no (or "
"almost no) viruses for this system**? Maybe because all editors (Adobe) or "
"manufacturers (NVidia) do not play the free game and do not provide a "
"version of their software or their __drivers__ for GNU/Linux? Fear of "
"change? The difficulty to find where to buy a Linux computer? Too few games "
"(but not for long) distributed under Linux? Will the situation change with "
"the arrival of the steam-box game console that runs on Linux?"
msgstr ""

