#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:169
msgid ""
"The **Gnome 3** desktop environment no longer uses the concept of Desktop "
"but that of Gnome Shell (not to be confused with the command line shell). It "
"serves as a desktop, a dashboard, a notification area and a window selector. "
"The Gnome desktop environment is based on the GTK+ component library."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:171
msgid "![KDE Desktop](images/01-presentation-kde.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:173
msgid ""
"The **KDE** desktop environment is based on the **Qt** component library."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:175
msgid ""
"It is traditionally more recommended for users coming from a Windows world."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:177
msgid "![Tux - The Linux mascot](images/tux.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:179
msgid "### Free / Open source"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:181
msgid ""
"A user of a Microsoft or Mac operating system must purchase a license to use "
"the operating system. This license has a cost, although it is usually "
"transparent (the price of the license is included in the price of the "
"computer)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:183
msgid ""
"In the **GNU/Linux** world, the Free Software movement provides mostly free "
"distributions."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:185
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Free** does not mean free!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:187
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Open source**: the source codes are available, so it is possible to consult and modify them under certain conditions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:189
msgid ""
"A free software is necessarily Open Source, but the opposite is not true "
"since an Open Source software is separated from the freedom proposed by the "
"GPL license."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:191
msgid "#### GPL License (General Public License)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:193
msgid ""
"The **GPL License** guarantees the author of a software its intellectual "
"property, but allows modification, redistribution or resale of software by "
"third parties, provided that the source codes are provided with the "
"software. The GPL is the license that came out of the **GNU** (GNU is Not "
"UNIX) project, which was instrumental in creating Linux."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:195
msgid "It implies :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:200
msgid "the freedom to run the program, for any purpose;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:200
msgid "the freedom to study how the program works and adapt it to your needs"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:200
msgid "the freedom to redistribute copies;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:200
msgid ""
"the freedom to improve the program and publish your improvements, for the "
"benefit of the whole community."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:202
msgid ""
"On the other hand, even products licensed under the GPL can be paid for. "
"This is not the product itself, but the guarantee that a team of developers "
"will continue to work on it to make it evolve and troubleshoot errors, or "
"even provide support to users."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:204
msgid "## Areas of use"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
